        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>content audit</strong> is a systematic review of all content on a website — evaluating each page's performance, relevance, and quality — to decide what to <strong>keep, update, consolidate, redirect, or delete</strong>. It surfaces content decay, keyword cannibalization, and thin pages that dilute overall site quality signals.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Rankings lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">65% (Semrush)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Annual + quarterly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most sites do not have a content problem. They have a content clutter problem. Every published page is a promise to Google that you'll maintain it. When 40% of pages are decayed or ignored, Google downgrades the site as a whole. A content audit is how you take the promise back.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a content audit?</h2>
        <p>A content audit is a full inventory-and-evaluation of every URL on your site — blog posts, landing pages, category pages, PDFs, tag archives, everything indexable. For each URL you record traffic, rankings, backlinks, conversions, publication date, and topic. Then you tag each one with a decision: keep, update, consolidate, redirect, or delete.</p>
        <p>The output is not the spreadsheet. The output is the roadmap: which 20 pages to update this quarter, which 40 to merge into pillar guides, and which 60 to redirect out of the index. Site quality goes up. Crawl budget compresses onto pages that matter. Rankings follow.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance — the "helpful content" signal</div>
          <p>Since Google's helpful content system launched in 2022, site-wide quality is a ranking factor. Low-value content on a site can drag down high-value content on the same domain. Pruning unhelpful pages via a content audit measurably lifts survivors.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why a content audit matters</h2>
        <p>Five reasons audit debt compounds if you ignore it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Site-wide quality signals.</strong> Google evaluates helpfulness at the domain level. Thin content pulls the whole site down.</li>
          <li><strong>Crawl budget efficiency.</strong> Googlebot has a fixed crawl budget per site. Wasting it on zombie pages means fewer visits to pages you want indexed fast.</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword cannibalization.</strong> Multiple pages competing for the same query split rankings. Consolidation lets one strong page win.</li>
          <li><strong>Content decay recovery.</strong> Pages that once ranked #3 drift to #17 as content ages. Auditing surfaces them for a targeted refresh.</li>
          <li><strong>Editorial hygiene.</strong> Outdated stats, dead links, and old brand references erode trust with both readers and E-E-A-T signals.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a content audit works — the 5-step framework</h2>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The full workflow</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">1.</span> Inventory <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Every URL, from sitemap + crawl<br>
          <span class="uf-label">2.</span> Enrich <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Traffic, queries, backlinks, conversions<br>
          <span class="uf-label">3.</span> Score <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Tag each URL: keep / update / merge / redirect / delete<br>
          <span class="uf-label">4.</span> Act <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Execute the decisions in ranked order<br>
          <span class="uf-label">5.</span> Monitor <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-status">Re-check rankings + indexation over 30-90 days</span>
        </div>

        <h3>1. Inventory everything</h3>
        <p>Pull the XML sitemap. Run Screaming Frog or Sitebulb. Cross-check against Search Console's indexed pages. You want a single spreadsheet with every URL, title, meta description, word count, and publication date.</p>

        <h3>2. Enrich with performance data</h3>
        <p>Join GA4 traffic and engagement metrics, Search Console impressions and clicks, Ahrefs or Semrush backlink data, and any conversion attribution you have. This is the objective evidence for each decision.</p>

        <h3>3. Score and tag each URL</h3>
        <p>Apply a simple rubric: high traffic + high relevance = keep. High traffic + drift = update. Multiple pages on same topic = merge. Zero traffic + no backlinks + no unique value = delete.</p>

        <h3>4. Execute the decisions</h3>
        <p>Refresh the update pile first — highest ROI. Merge the duplicates into strongest survivors with 301 redirects from the losers. Delete zombies with 301s to relevant pages, or use 410 Gone if no match exists.</p>

        <h3>5. Monitor over 30-90 days</h3>
        <p>Watch Search Console impressions and average position on surviving pages. Rankings typically improve within 6-12 weeks after aggressive pruning.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Decision tags — what each one means</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Decision</th><th>When to apply</th><th>Action</th><th>Expected impact</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Keep</strong></td><td>High traffic, high relevance, current</td><td>Nothing — leave it</td><td>Ongoing performance</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Update</strong></td><td>Was ranking, now decayed</td><td>Refresh stats, examples, structure</td><td>Ranking recovery in 4-8 weeks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Consolidate/Merge</strong></td><td>3+ pages on similar topic</td><td>Merge into strongest, 301 rest</td><td>Reduces cannibalization</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Redirect</strong></td><td>Traffic, but topic no longer strategic</td><td>301 to relevant surviving page</td><td>Retains equity, cleans surface area</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Delete</strong></td><td>Zero traffic, no backlinks, no value</td><td>410 Gone or 301 + noindex</td><td>Lifts site-wide quality signal</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content audit examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Law firm — aggressive pruning</h3>
        <p>A regional law firm blog had 240 posts, 30% of which had zero traffic in 12 months. They deleted the zombie 30% (with topical 301s), refreshed the top 40 posts, and left the middle bucket alone. Surviving pages climbed an average of 4.2 positions over 90 days.</p>
        <h3>2. Ecommerce brand — consolidation win</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce brand had 12 blog posts on variations of "best running shoes" — all competing for the same queries. They merged all 12 into 3 pillar guides (best road, best trail, best for beginners), with 301s from the losers. Organic traffic to the pillar set doubled in 6 weeks.</p>
        <h3>3. SaaS company — decay-driven update</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company found 22 previously top-ranking blog posts that had drifted 5-15 positions. Instead of writing new content, they refreshed all 22 with 2026 stats, new screenshots, and expanded FAQs. 19 of 22 recovered original rankings within 8 weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content audit vs content gap analysis</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content audit</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Reviews what you already published</li>
              <li>Decides keep / update / delete for each URL</li>
              <li>Fixes decay, cannibalization, thin content</li>
              <li>Improves site-wide quality signals</li>
              <li>Cadence: annual + quarterly hits</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Content gap analysis</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Reviews what competitors rank for that you do not</li>
              <li>Decides which topics to publish next</li>
              <li>Fills coverage holes in topical clusters</li>
              <li>Grows keyword footprint</li>
              <li>Cadence: quarterly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Run both. Audit clears the deck; gap analysis fills the roadmap.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 content audit best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Score against a rubric, not a gut feel.</strong> Use consistent thresholds — e.g. "zero organic clicks in 12 months + zero backlinks + zero conversions = delete candidate".</li>
          <li><strong>Redirect to the closest topical match, not the homepage.</strong> Mass homepage 301s are treated as soft 404s by Google.</li>
          <li><strong>Preserve legal, product, and doc pages.</strong> These do not need traffic to justify their existence.</li>
          <li><strong>Batch refresh work by topical cluster.</strong> Updating 8 posts in one cluster is faster than 8 unrelated posts and lifts the cluster together.</li>
          <li><strong>Track before/after in one dashboard.</strong> Rankings, impressions, clicks per audited URL — measured 30/60/90 days after action.</li>
          <li><strong>Run a mini-audit quarterly.</strong> Only top 50 pages. Catches decay before it becomes a full-audit problem.</li>
          <li><strong>Document the decision log.</strong> Six months later you'll want to remember why you deleted a specific URL. Keep the record.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — deleting URLs with backlinks</div>
          <p>Before you delete, check backlinks in Ahrefs or Semrush. A URL with 20 referring domains has SEO value even at zero organic traffic. Always 301 it to a relevant page instead of returning 410 or 404.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content audit mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Auditing only by traffic.</strong> Pages can matter for conversions, backlinks, or brand — traffic is one lens, not all.</li>
          <li><strong>Mass 301 to homepage.</strong> Google treats these as soft 404s. Map each redirect to a topical match.</li>
          <li><strong>Deleting without checking backlinks.</strong> Kills authority you already earned.</li>
          <li><strong>Refreshing every page.</strong> Ineffective — focus updates on pages within striking distance of first page.</li>
          <li><strong>No post-audit measurement.</strong> If you cannot show ranking recovery in 90 days, you cannot justify the next audit.</li>
          <li><strong>Auditing once, forever.</strong> Content decays continuously. One audit is a snapshot, not a strategy.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How often should you do a content audit?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Run a full site-wide content audit once every 12-18 months. In parallel, run quarterly mini-audits on your top 50 pages by traffic to catch content decay before rankings drop.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How long does a content audit take?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Expect 1-2 days for a site with 100-200 URLs, and about a week for sites with 500+ URLs. Larger enterprise sites (5,000+ URLs) can take 3-6 weeks depending on how deep you evaluate each page.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
