            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google Analytics 4 (traffic and engagement), Google Search Console (queries and impressions), a crawl tool like Screaming Frog or Sitebulb, a rank tracker like Ahrefs or Semrush, and a spreadsheet or Airtable base to tag decisions.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What should you delete during a content audit?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Delete pages with zero traffic for 12+ months, no backlinks, no revenue attribution, and no unique value that lives elsewhere. Always 301 redirect deleted URLs to the most relevant surviving page — never bulk-redirect to the homepage.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between a content audit and a content gap analysis?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A content audit reviews what you already have and decides what to keep. A content gap analysis identifies what you should publish next — topics competitors rank for but you do not. Both are complementary, not substitutes.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

